Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Zest and juice the @orange{1/2}. Put both the zest and
juice in a #mixing bowl{}. Add the @soy sauce{1.5} and a sprinkling of @?sugar{} if
you have some. Mix together, then add the @pork medallion{2} and make sure it is
well coated in the marinade. Set aside to marinate while you prepare everything
else.

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1} into half moons. Halve, then remove
the core from the @red pepper{1} and chop into 2cm pieces. Remove the top and
bottom from the @courgette{1} and chop into 2cm chunks. Twist and tear the
@flat leaf parsley{1/2%bunch} in half and roughly chop. Put the pepper and courgette
on a lined #baking tray{} and drizzle with @oil{drizzle}. Season with @salt{} and
@black pepper{}. Roast on the top shelf of your oven, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #small saucepan{} on low heat and add the
onion. Stir and cook until soft, ~{10%minutes}. Add the @balsamic vinegar{1} and
cook gently until the onion is caramelised, another ~{10%minutes}. Put a #lid{} on
the pan, take it off the heat and set aside.

In the meantime pour the @water{300%ml} into a large #saucepan{} and add the
@chicken stock pot{1/2}. Bring to the boil and stir to dissolve the stock pot, then
add the @couscous{150%g} with a drizzle of @olive oil{}. Take the pan off the heat,
put a lid on and set aside so the couscous absorbs the stock.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat. Lay in the pork (leave
the marinade in the bowl for now). Cook until slightly caramelised, ~{7-8%minutes}
on each side.

> TIP: The pork is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Remove from the pan and rest on a #board{} for a few mins. Cover with #foil{} to
keep warm. Add the marinade to your now empty pan and simmer for ~{2%minutes}.

Fluff up the couscous with a #fork{}. Add the roasted veggies, the caramelised
onion and half the parsley. Stir everything together. Slice the pork into roughly
1cm wide slices. Serve the couscous in bowls with the pork on top. Drizzle with a
good spoonful of the soy and orange sauce and sprinkle on the remaining parsley.
Enjoy!